The fundamental hurdle is that when CSS creates triangles using the border trick, they essentially appear as arrows pointing up or down because the “triangle” is technically the transparent half of a square’s border. Thus, constructing a pentagram (a star with interconnected lines) from separate triangle elements in CSS will not replicate the traditional line-connected pentagram without overlaid elements or SVG for precise shapes.

However, to follow the task as closely as permitted by CSS and HTML alone, you can arrange five divs (as triangles) in a circle and rotate each to simulate the pentagram’s star points. Note, this will not create the interconnected star lines seen in classic pentagrams but will position triangles in an approximation.

