Creating two arrowhead-like shapes in CSS and aligning them to overlap in a way that resembles parts of a pentagram or star can be done using CSS’s capabilities for drawing shapes (usually through the manipulation of borders for invisible elements) and then utilizing transformations for positioning and rotation. This approach can simulate more complex shapes by intersecting simpler ones.

Let’s demonstrate this concept by creating two overlapping arrowhead shapes that might resemble the top of a pentagram when aligned correctly. Remember, this is a simplified example and depending on the precision and exact appearance you’re aiming for, you might need to adjust sizes, angles, and positions.


<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang=“en”>
<head>
<meta charset=“UTF-8”>
<title>Overlap Arrowheads</title>
<style>
  .arrowhead {
    width: 0;
    height: 0;
    border-left: 50px solid transparent;
    border-right: 50px solid transparent;
  }
  .upward {
    border-bottom: 100px solid black; /* Bottom border creates the upward arrowhead /
    position: absolute;
    transform: translateX(-50%) rotate(-20deg); / Adjust rotation and position as needed /
  }
  .downward {
    border-top: 100px solid black; / Top border creates the downward arrowhead /
    position: absolute;
    transform: translate(-50%, -100%) rotate(20deg); / Overlap and rotate the second arrowhead */
  }
</style>
</head>
<body>

<div class=“arrowhead upward”></div>
<div class=“arrowhead downward”></div>

</body>
</html>



In this example, two &lt;div&gt; elements with the class .arrowhead are styled to appear as arrowheads pointing upward and downward, respectively. The border-left and border-right properties are used to create the triangular arrowhead shape, while the border-bottom or border-top properties give the arrowheads their solid appearance.

The .upward and .downward classes apply additional styles:
- The .upward arrowhead uses a bottom border to become solid and is rotated slightly to mimic a possible section of a pentagram’s arm.
- The .downward arrowhead uses a top border to emulate the solid part pointing downwards and overlaps the first arrowhead with some rotation to aim for a visually complex intersection.

Both are positioned absolutely from a common parent (the &lt;body&gt; in this case, for simplicity) and use transform to adjust their placement and angle.

This example is greatly simplified and focuses on demonstrating how to overlap shapes creatively with CSS. Creating a full pentagram or more intricate designs would require more shapes and precise adjustments. This approach shows how CSS can manipulate simple elements to create more complex visuals, but for a full pentagram, particularly with perfect geometric accuracy, using SVG would still be more effective and efficient.
